President Gjorge Ivanov has said that he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has led to doubts if the minimum participation of 50% required for the referendum to be considered valid will be achieved.
The issue of the ballot in the referendum is this: "Are you for NATO and EU membership with the approval of the agreement with Greece?"
However, the name change supporters, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that changing names is worth allowing Macedonia, one of the countries that was formed when Yugoslavia was split, to join the EU and NATO.
"I am here to vote for the future of our country, for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because that means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
The follow-up vote is not binding, but sufficient Members of Parliament have said that they intend to follow the outcome in order for it to be considered decisive.
The change in names requires a majority of two thirds of Parliament.
According to the State Electoral Commission, no irregularities had been reported at 1 p.m.
However, participation was only 16 per cent, compared with 34 per cent in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66 per cent of registered voters voted.
"I vote for my children's sake, we belong in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital Skopje.
Prime Minister of Macedonia Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko are voting in the referendum in Macedonia on the country's change of name, which would open the way for membership in NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia 30 September 2018.
Outside the European Parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, organized a small stage and placed chairs in front of the tents set up by those who boycott the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to go with our head in the air, not sneak in through the back door," said Kavardarkov.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they do not welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, such as China and Russia, and become part of Euro-Asian integration."
According to Prime Minister Zaev, NATO membership would lead to a necessary investment in Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20%.
"I believe that the absolute majority will vote yes, for over 80% of our citizens are for the EU and NATO," said Zaev when he voted.
He said that a "yes" result would be a "confirmation of our future".
