Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, "Why can't I know this until now, in my last year?"
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was organised for the first time this year, explains to the students the importance of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University's health care services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that the students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course includes a range of interactive tasks.
In a part of the course there is an image of a student room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another section, participants will learn how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not change the behaviour of the students directly.
But we think they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know about the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in "during" still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that lack of sleep was a growing problem.
To ensure that you have enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's "secret weapon" to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain because sleeplessness puts the brain in starve mode and makes them ever hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course and has studied one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course was an eye opener and inspired him to campaign for a campus course.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar study program before they start their studies at the high-performance institution.
