Flat muscle populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have decreased significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by building and development work that affects the yield and loss of habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as aircraft and certain chemical treatments of building materials as well as domestic attacks.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes in catching the prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-localisation technique to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats seriously.
